eteenth and twentieth centuries. As well as examining ‘what nurses did’, it explores the significance and meaning of nursing work, for nurses themselves, their patients and their communities, and examines developments in practice against a backdrop of social, cultural, political and economic drivers and constraints.This book will be of interest to academics and clinical nurses alike. It is also an ideal textbook for undergraduate nursing programmes, providing students with rich accounts of the history of their own disciplinary practice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aNursingxCongressesxHistory. 0aNursingxHistoryvCongresses. 0aNursingxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aAustralian nurses.  aNew Zealand nurses.  aWorld War I.  achild healthcare.  acholera epidemic.  ahands-on' clinical work.  ahealth education.  ahealth screening.  ainfant healthcare.  amalnutrition.  amodern health system.  amortality rates.  apublic health crisis management.  asanatorium nursing.  askilled nursing practice.  asocial hygiene.1 aApple, Rima D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlessing, Bettina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoschma, Geertje, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrodie, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrooks, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDietz, Susanne Malchau, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDietz, Susanne, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFealy, Gerard M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFealy, Gerard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/